## Migration: .NET Framework → .NET 8

### Critical Breaking Changes

1. **`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** in .NET 8 — it no longer works at all
2. **`ThreadAbortException` is never raised** — your catch block is dead code
3. **`Thread.ResetAbort()` also throws** `PlatformNotSupportedException`

### Root Problem

The old pattern relied on the CLR's cooperative thread abort mechanism. .NET 8 removed this entirely. You need `CancellationToken` for cooperative cancellation.

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Task? _workerTask;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        var token = _cts.Token;
        _workerTask = Task.Run(() => ProcessLoop(token), token);
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                // Pass token so blocking calls can be interrupted immediately
                var item = GetNextItem(token);
                ProcessItem(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Cancellation requested — clean up partial work
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                break; // exit the loop (no ResetAbort equivalent needed)
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public async Task StopAsync(TimeSpan? timeout = null)
    {
        if (_cts is null || _workerTask is null)
            return;

        // Signal cancellation (replaces _running = false + Thread.Abort)
        _cts.Cancel();

        // Wait with timeout instead of Thread.Sleep + Abort
        var effectiveTimeout = timeout ?? TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5);
        if (await Task.WhenAny(_workerTask, Task.Delay(effectiveTimeout)) != _workerTask)
        {
            // Task didn't finish in time — it's likely stuck in unmanaged code.
            // Log a warning; there is NO safe equivalent of Abort() in .NET 8.
            Log.Warning("Worker did not stop within timeout");
        }
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        _cts?.Cancel();
        _workerTask?.Wait(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2));
        _cts?.Dispose();
    }
}
```

### Key Migration Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---|---|
| **Blocking calls ignore cancellation** | If `GetNextItem()` blocks on a `Monitor.Wait`, `Socket.Read`, or DB call that doesn't accept a `CancellationToken`, cancellation won't interrupt it. You **must** refactor those calls to accept tokens. |
| **No forced kill exists** | .NET 8 has no replacement for `Thread.Abort()`. If code is truly stuck (e.g., in unmanaged P/Invoke), you cannot forcibly stop it in-process. The only escape hatch is `Environment.FailFast()` or running the work in a separate **process**. |
| **`catch (ThreadAbortException)` was auto-rethrown** | In Framework, `ThreadAbortException` re-threw at the end of the catch block unless `ResetAbort()` was called. `OperationCanceledException` does **not** auto-rethrow — you must `break` or `return` yourself. |
| **`volatile bool` is insufficient** | The old `_running` flag couldn't interrupt blocking calls. `CancellationToken` can — but only if you pass it into the blocking API. |
| **Thread → Task** | `Task.Run` uses the thread pool (more efficient). If you need a dedicated long-running thread, use `Task.Factory.StartNew(..., TaskCreationOptions.LongRunning)`. |

### If You Can't Refactor Blocking Calls

As a last resort, you can interrupt a raw thread with `Thread.Interrupt()` (still supported), which throws `ThreadInterruptedException` in blocking calls like `Thread.Sleep`, `Monitor.Wait`, etc.:

```csharp
// Escape hatch — NOT recommended over CancellationToken
_workerThread.Interrupt(); // throws ThreadInterruptedException in the target
```

This only works for managed blocking; it won't interrupt unmanaged/IO calls.
